b'' b'' b'my top list of dumbest automotive concepts ever' b'' b"9. back-up lights on corvette they're on the sides of the car!" b' b'sure would be interested to know what year(s) this was!' b"i don't seem to recall any car with back-up lights on the sides, much" b'less any corvette. i suppose i could be mis-interpreting what you are' b'trying to say here.....' b'' b'just a quick comment. backup lights mounted on the side' b'would actually be *extremely* useful for people backing out of' b'parking stalls...' b'' b"while i can't think of any corvettes with side mounted backup lights," b'i know that saab started using them about years ago. my saab b"didn't have them, but a friend's saab certainly did. in addition" b'to the confentional tail-light mounted backup lights, they had another' b'set integrated into the front turn signal assembly. for those of you who' b"don't remember, saabs of that vintage had an enormous multicoloured plastic" b'growth, about the size of a _national geographic_ magazine, sticking out' b'of the front fender, which incorporated amber "parking lights", amber side' b'marker lights/reflectors, white "cornering lamps" (like american luxury' b'cars) aimed towards the side of the road when you have your turn indicators' b'on, and white "backup lights" aimed towards the back of the car when you' b'have selected reverse gear. the glossy brochure showed how these front' b"mounted backup lights were useful for illuminating hazards (pot holes, kid's" b'toys, etc) that would be run over by the front of the car if you had the' b'wheels turned while backing up.' b'' b'mart l. molle' b'computer systems research institute' b'university of toronto' b'toronto, canada m5s 1a4' b'(416)978-4928' 